34:14.907 --> 34:17.029
Another thing I was interested in was those early 
tests, like Bikini and some of the other ones, do

34:18.545 --> 34:32.580
you remember what your first impressions were 
when you saw your first nuclear explosion or

34:18.545 --> 34:32.580
atomic explosion? Yes. I was on one

34:36.324 --> 34:47.235
of our communications ships—I've forgotten the 
name of it now—in Bikini or just out of Bikini

34:48.194 --> 34:49.876
Lagoon. When the shot was fired, it was one drop 
from an airplane and one off at two thousand feet

34:51.278 --> 35:00.269
about.

35:03.272 --> 35:07.137
Maybe not quite that high, I've forgotten 
exactly, but it was an air burst anyway. And it was

35:09.260 --> 35:16.969
my first view of a chain reaction of a nuclear 
detonation, a nuclear explosion.

35:21.387 --> 35:49.048
and the suddenness and the magnitudes

35:21.387 --> 35:49.048
and the disruption

35:21.387 --> 35:49.048
that was caused by it, all within milliseconds, 
was something that's a little difficult for your

35:21.387 --> 35:49.048
mind to follow unless you've had some practice, 
and I had no practice at that point. And of course,

35:51.104 --> 36:20.757
in the South Pacific, with the very, very moist 
air, with the shock wave ballooning out from the

35:51.104 --> 36:20.757
explosion, and it formed a

35:51.104 --> 36:20.757
dense cloud in the form of a diving bell with the 
bottom on the surface of the water that gradually

35:51.104 --> 36:20.757
expanded and went out. this

36:21.580 --> 36:39.142
huge explosion with all of its colors and boiling 
and disruption was suddenly closed in this diving

36:21.580 --> 36:39.142
bell of clouds. And almost equally quickly, that 
was dispersed by the heat. And so it was a very

36:46.331 --> 36:50.136
spectacular show.

36:51.500 --> 37:16.377
if you were thinking in terms of being on target

36:51.500 --> 37:16.377
and comparing that with

36:51.500 --> 37:16.377
being on target against other weapons that we had 
